I think it's related to closed #929. Filed this just in case - I spent several hours trying to understand what's wrong with my code.

`intersectRayTriangle (Ray ray, Vector3 t1, Vector3 t2, Vector3 t3, Vector3 intersection) ` returns `true` for any [degenerate triangle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degeneracy_(mathematics)).

```
Ray ray = new Ray(new Vector3(10, 20, 30), new Vector3(0, -1, 0));

Vector3 tmp1 = new Vector3(100, 200, 300);
Vector3 tmp2 = new Vector3(400, 500, 600);
Vector3 tmp3 = new Vector3(400, 500, 600); // same as tmp2

boolean result = Intersector.intersectRayTriangle(ray, tmp1, tmp2, tmp3, tmp);
```
Returned result is `true`, which I'm think is wrong. It also returns true for any one-point-triangle (and (0, 0, 0), (0, 0, 0), (0, 0, 0)).

IMO there is a little difference between "edge case with float precision" and "incorrect input data causes false positive".

